#1 Stage IIA colon cancer
We discussed with Dr. Fenwick the controversy surrounding adjuvant therapy for stage II colon cancer.  He does not have any of the high-risk features for stage II disease such as a T4 lesion, fewer than 13 lymph nodes removed, poorly-differentiated cancer with signet cell or mucinous features.  In addition, the microsatellite instability present is known to carry a better prognosis and to predict for lack of adjuvant therapy benefit.
Based on the available evidence, our recommendations would be to not proceed with adjuvant chemotherapy.  We discussed there is a good chance for cure, and we are not certain whether adjuvant chemotherapy would again increase the chance of survival in this situation.
We discussed that giving him the microsatellite instability, genetic consultation would be recommended to discuss testing for these abnormalities looking for somatic mutations of the DNA gene repair mechanism. Dr. Fenwick is going to Slagle shortly and would follow-up with physician recommendations there.
We discussed follow-up for this type of colon cancer which would involve history, physical examination, and imaging studies every three or six-month basis.
Dr. Fenwick was appreciative of the information.  I discussed with him that he should feel to call with questions or concerns in the future.  He may be coming back in three-months, and he will let us know if he is interested in following-up here at that time, although he will make an appointment and develop a relationship with a medical oncologist in Slagle where he lives.  We will be happy to forward any imaging studies or records there at his request.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

