[start section id="20102"]

Stage II colon cancer.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Dr. Fenwick is a 50-year-old gentleman, who developed anemia.  Colonoscopy found a mass in the ascending colon, and it was biopsy-proven to be adenocarcinoma.  The patient had staging workup with CT of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis which was negative, other than the suggestion of a mass in the ascending colon.  He underwent surgery on the 22nd of June.  An 8.5-cm mass was found, grade 3 out of 4 adenocarcinoma, with tumor invading through the muscularis propria and into the pericolic fat, negative margins, and all 38 lymph nodes negative for cancer (T3, N0).
Microsatellite instability testing was performed.  By immunohistochemistry, there was loss of MLH-1 and PMS-2 and retention of MSH-2 and MSH-6.  By BCR assay, there was instability in 5 out of 5 informative markers (MSI-H).
Dr. Fenwick is here with his father who is a waqhqog lgzthxzgnmd at the Spencer Municipal Medical Center to discuss adjuvant options.

[end section id="20103"]

